    "In particular, US college-educated voters-who broke for Clinton in 2016 by a significant margin-were substantially more likely to respond to pollsters in key swing-states, and less than 1 3 of swing-state polls adjusted their estimates for education levels on average.",
    "In the UK, comparisons of pre-election polls microdata with known representative samples from the British Election Study and the British Social Attitudes survey showed polls tended to under-sample conservative voters between 45 and 65 years of age, and across multiple regions in England.",
